    {
      "content": "Azure Notification Hubs - Diagnosis Guidelines",
      "pos": [
        28,
        74
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Guidelines on how to diagnose common issues with Azure Notification Hubs.",
      "pos": [
        94,
        167
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure Notification Hubs - Diagnosis guidelines",
      "pos": [
        498,
        544
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Overview",
      "pos": [
        548,
        556
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "One of the most common questions we hear from Azure Notification Hubs customers is how to figure out why they donâ€™t see a notification sent from their application backend appear on the client device - where and why notifications were dropped and how to fix this.",
      "pos": [
        558,
        820
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this article we will go through the various reasons why notifications may get dropped or do not end up on the devices.",
      "pos": [
        821,
        942
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "We will also look through ways in which you can analyze and figure out the root cause.",
      "pos": [
        943,
        1029
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "First of all, it is critical to understand how Azure Notification Hubs pushes out notifications to the devices.",
      "pos": [
        1032,
        1143
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![][0]",
      "pos": [
        1144,
        1150
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In a typical send notification flow, the message is sent from the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>application backend<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Azure Notification Hub (NH)<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> which in turn does some processing on all the registrations taking into account the configured tags &amp; tag expressions to determine \"targets\" i.e. all the registrations that need to receive the push notification.",
      "pos": [
        1152,
        1488
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These registrations can span across any or all of our supported platforms - iOS, Google, Windows, Windows Phone, Kindle and Baidu for China Android.",
      "pos": [
        1489,
        1637
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once the targets are established, NH then pushes out notifications, split across multiple batch of registrations, to the device platform specific <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Push Notification Service (PNS)<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> - e.g. APNS for Apple, GCM for Google etc. NH authenticates with the respective PNS based on the credentials you set in the Azure Portal on the Configure Notification Hub page.",
      "pos": [
        1638,
        1996
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The PNS then forwards the notifications to the respective <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>client devices<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        1997,
        2074
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is the platform recommended way to deliver push notifications and note that the final leg of notification delivery takes place between the platform PNS and the device.",
      "pos": [
        2075,
        2247
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Therefore we have four major components - <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>client<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>application backend<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept>, <bpt id=\"p3\">*</bpt>Azure Notification Hubs (NH)<ept id=\"p3\">*</ept> and <bpt id=\"p4\">*</bpt>Push Notification Services (PNS)<ept id=\"p4\">*</ept> and any of these may cause notifications getting dropped.",
      "pos": [
        2248,
        2450
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "More details on this architecture is available on <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Notification Hubs Overview]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        2451,
        2530
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Failure to deliver notifications may happen during the initial test/staging phase which may indicate a configuration issue or it may happen in production where either all or some of the notifications may be getting dropped indicating some deeper application or messaging pattern issue.",
      "pos": [
        2532,
        2817
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the section, below we will look at various dropped notifications scenarios ranging from common to the rarer kind, some of which you may find obvious and some others not so much.",
      "pos": [
        2818,
        2998
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure Notifications Hub mis-configuration",
      "pos": [
        3003,
        3044
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure Notification Hubs needs to authenticate itself in the context of the developer's application to be able to successfully send notifications to the respective PNS.",
      "pos": [
        3047,
        3214
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is made possible by the developer creating a developer account with the respective platform (Google, Apple, Windows etc) and then registering their application where they get credentials which need to be configured in the Azure portal under Notification Hubs configuration section.",
      "pos": [
        3215,
        3501
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If no notifications are making through, first step should be to ensure that the correct credentials are configured in the Notification Hub matching them with the application created under their platform specific developer account.",
      "pos": [
        3502,
        3732
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You will find our <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Getting Started Tutorials]</ept> useful to go over this process in a step by step manner.",
      "pos": [
        3733,
        3835
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Here are some common mis-configurations:",
      "pos": [
        3836,
        3876
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "General",
      "pos": [
        3883,
        3890
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "a) Make sure that your notification hub name (without typos) is the same:",
      "pos": [
        3899,
        3972
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Where you are registering from the client,",
      "pos": [
        3980,
        4022
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Where you are sending notifications from the backend,",
      "pos": [
        4030,
        4083
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Where you have configured the PNS credentials and",
      "pos": [
        4092,
        4141
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Whose SAS credentials you have configured on the client and the backend.",
      "pos": [
        4149,
        4221
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "b) Make sure that you are using the correct SAS configuration strings on the client and the application backend.",
      "pos": [
        4236,
        4348
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As a rule of thumb, you must be using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>DefaultListenSharedAccessSignature<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> on the client and <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>DefaultFullSharedAccessSignature<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> on the application backend (which gives permission to be able to send notification to the NH)",
      "pos": [
        4349,
        4578
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Apple Push Notification Service (APNS) configuration",
      "pos": [
        4585,
        4637
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You must maintain two different hubs - one for production and another for testing purpose.",
      "pos": [
        4646,
        4736
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This means uploading the certificate you are going to use in sandbox environment to a separate hub and the certificate you are going to use in production to a separate hub.",
      "pos": [
        4737,
        4909
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Do not try to upload different types of certificates to the same hub as it may cause notification failures down the line.",
      "pos": [
        4910,
        5031
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you do find yourself in a position where you have inadvertently uploaded different types of certificate to the same hub, it is recommended to delete the hub and start fresh.",
      "pos": [
        5032,
        5208
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If for some reason, you are not able to delete the hub then at the very least, you must delete all the existing registrations from the hub.",
      "pos": [
        5209,
        5348
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Google Cloud Messaging (GCM) configuration",
      "pos": [
        5356,
        5398
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "a) Make sure that you are enabling \"Google Cloud Messaging for Android\" under your cloud project.",
      "pos": [
        5407,
        5504
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![][2]",
      "pos": [
        5515,
        5521
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "b) Make sure that you create a \"Server Key\" while obtaining the credentials which NH will use to authenticate with GCM.",
      "pos": [
        5531,
        5650
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![][3]",
      "pos": [
        5661,
        5667
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "c) Make sure that you have configured \"Project ID\" on the client which is an entirely numerical entity that you can obtain from the dashboard:",
      "pos": [
        5677,
        5819
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![][1]",
      "pos": [
        5829,
        5835
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Application issues",
      "pos": [
        5839,
        5857
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Tags/ Tag expressions",
      "pos": [
        5864,
        5885
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are using tags or tag expressions to segment your audience, it is always possible that when you are sending the notification, there is no target being found based on the tags/tag expressions you are specifying in your send call.",
      "pos": [
        5889,
        6124
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is best to review your registrations to ensure that there are tags which match when you send notification and then verify the notification receipt only from the clients with those registrations.",
      "pos": [
        6125,
        6322
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "E.g.",
      "pos": [
        6323,
        6327
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "if all your registrations with NH were done with say tag \"Politics\" and you are sending a notification with tag \"Sports\", it will not be sent to any device.",
      "pos": [
        6328,
        6484
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A complex case could involve tag expressions where you only registered with \"Tag A\" OR \"Tag B\" but while sending notifications, you are targeting \"Tag A &amp;&amp; Tag B\".",
      "pos": [
        6485,
        6648
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the self-diagnose tips section below, there are ways in which you can review your registrations along with the tags they have.",
      "pos": [
        6649,
        6778
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Template issues",
      "pos": [
        6786,
        6801
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6805,
        6915
      ],
      "content": "If you are using templates then ensure that you are following the guidelines described at <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Template guidance]</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Invalid registrations",
      "pos": [
        6923,
        6944
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Assuming the Notification Hub was configured correctly and any tags/tag expressions were used correctly resulting in the find of valid targets to which the notifications need to be sent, NH fires off several processing batches in parallel - each batch sending messages to a set of registrations.",
      "pos": [
        6948,
        7243
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        7248,
        7375
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Since we do the processing in parallel, we donâ€™t guarantee the order in which the notifications will be delivered."
    },
    {
      "content": "Now Azure Notifications Hub is optimized for an \"at-most once\" message delivery model.",
      "pos": [
        7378,
        7464
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This means that we attempt a de-duplication so that no notifications are delivered more than once to a device.",
      "pos": [
        7465,
        7575
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To ensure this we look through the registrations and make sure that only one message is sent per device identifier before actually sending the message to the PNS.",
      "pos": [
        7576,
        7738
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As each batch is sent to the PNS, which in turn is accepting and validating the registrations, it is possible that the PNS detects an error with one or more of the registrations in a batch, returns an error to Azure NH and stops processing thereby dropping that batch completely.",
      "pos": [
        7739,
        8018
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is especially true with APNS which uses a TCP stream protocol.",
      "pos": [
        8019,
        8086
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Since we are optimized for at-most once delivery, it is to be noted that there is no retry for this failed batch since we do not know for sure if the PNS dropped the entire batch or partially.",
      "pos": [
        8087,
        8279
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "PNS does however tell Azure NH which registration caused the failure and based on the feedback we remove that registration from our database.",
      "pos": [
        8280,
        8421
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This implies that it is possible that one registration batch or a subset of it may not receive a notification however since we cleaned up the bad registration, the next time a send is attempted, there is a higher chance of successful send.",
      "pos": [
        8422,
        8661
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As the scale of number of target devices grow (some of our customers send notification to millions of devices), dropping an odd batch here and there doesnâ€™t make much difference in the overall percentage of devices receiving notifications however if you are sending a few notifications and there are some PNS errors then you may see either all or most notifications not getting received.",
      "pos": [
        8662,
        9049
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are seeing this behavior repeatedly then you must identify any bad registrations and delete them.",
      "pos": [
        9050,
        9154
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You must definitely delete any hand-formed registrations as they are the most common cause of dropped notifications.",
      "pos": [
        9155,
        9271
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If this is a test environment, you may also directly delete all the registrations as the apps when opened on the devices will retry and re-register with the Notification Hubs ensuring that all registrations there forth created will be valid ones.",
      "pos": [
        9272,
        9518
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "PNS issues",
      "pos": [
        9523,
        9533
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once the notification message has been received by the respective PNS then it is its responsibility to deliver the notification to the device.",
      "pos": [
        9535,
        9677
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure Notification Hubs is out of the picture here and has no control on when or if the notification is going to be delivered to the device.",
      "pos": [
        9678,
        9818
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Since the platform notification services are pretty robust, notifications do tend to reach the devices in a few seconds from the PNS.",
      "pos": [
        9819,
        9952
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the PNS however is throttling then Azure Notification Hubs does apply an exponential back off strategy and if the PNS remains unreachable for 30 min then we have a policy in place to expire and drop those messages permanently.",
      "pos": [
        9953,
        10182
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If a PNS attempts to deliver a notification but the device is offline, the notification is stored by the PNS for a limited period of time, and delivered to the device when it becomes available.",
      "pos": [
        10185,
        10378
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Only one recent notification for a particular app is stored.",
      "pos": [
        10379,
        10439
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If multiple notifications are sent while the device is offline, each new notification causes the prior notification to be discarded.",
      "pos": [
        10440,
        10572
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This behavior of keeping only the newest notification is referred to as coalescing notifications in APNS and collapsing in GCM (which uses a collapsing key).",
      "pos": [
        10573,
        10730
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the device remains offline for a long time, any notifications that were being stored for it are discarded.",
      "pos": [
        10731,
        10840
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Source - <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">APNS guidance]</ept> &amp; <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p2\">GCM guidance]</ept>",
      "pos": [
        10842,
        10883
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        10885,
        11127
      ],
      "content": "With Azure Notification Hubs - you can pass a coalescing key via an HTTP header using the generic <ph id=\"ph1\">`SendNotification`</ph> API (e.g. for .NET SDK â€“ <ph id=\"ph2\">`SendNotificationAsync`</ph>) which also takes HTTP headers which are passes as is to the respective PNS."
    },
    {
      "content": "Self-diagnose tips",
      "pos": [
        11132,
        11150
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Here we will examine the various avenues to diagnose and root cause any Notification Hub issues:",
      "pos": [
        11152,
        11248
      ]
    },
